Firehose, stream analytics, and M-S-K.

Kinesis Data Firehose is the managed delivery sibling of Data Streams. Where Data Streams is a stream you build consumers against, Firehose is a one-way pipe: you point it at a destination, hand it data, and it delivers, buffering and batching along the way, with no shards to manage, no consumers to write, and no checkpointing. The trade-off is that Firehose stores nothing; it's a delivery pipe, not a stream, so records that fail delivery can be backed up to S3, but you can't replay history. Its destinations are S3, the most common, which pairs with Athena or Glue downstream; Redshift, where Firehose writes to S3 first then issues a copy; OpenSearch, for real-time dashboards; H-T-T-P endpoints; and third parties like Splunk and Datadog. It batches records by buffer size, one to a hundred twenty-eight megabytes, or by a time interval, and it can run a Lambda transform inline, plus Parquet or O-R-C conversion. Streams versus Firehose: use Streams when you build your own consumers and need replay; use Firehose when you just want data delivered to a destination.

Managed Service for Apache Flink, formerly Kinesis Data Analytics, runs real-time analytics over streams, using Flink in Java, Scala, or Python, or using S-Q-L. It does windowed aggregations, tumbling, sliding, and session windows, stream joins, and anomaly detection, writing results back to a stream or to Firehose, fully managed with no Flink cluster to operate. Use it for per-minute dashboard metrics, threshold alerts, and on-stream E-T-L.

Amazon M-S-K is fully managed Apache Kafka: topics, partitions, brokers, and consumer groups, the standard Kafka model, with AWS handling broker provisioning, patching, and multi-A-Z deployment, so existing Kafka producers, consumers, and connectors work without code changes. It comes as M-S-K provisioned, where you size the brokers, or M-S-K Serverless, which auto-scales. Kinesis versus M-S-K: choose Kinesis if you're AWS-native and want zero operations; choose M-S-K if you already run Kafka or need its ecosystem.
